    <h4><span class="highlight">Our Past</span></h4>

    <p>OPOWER founders Dan Yates and Alex Laskey met their first week of college. After graduation, Dan started a software business he later sold to Houghton Mifflin, while Alex ran political campaigns. Though Alex has always been an environmentally aware outdoorsman, it was during a journey from Alaska to Patagonia that Dan became truly aware of ways our demand for energy devastates the natural world.</p>

    <p>When OPOWER was starting up in 2007, everyone was abuzz about cleaner energy production using renewable energy sources, like the sun and wind. Dan and Alex knew that, though critically important, these sources wouldn’t be tapped in the short-term. The answer to reducing our carbon emissions right now was curbing wasteful use of the types of energy we produce today.</p>

    <div class="clearfix">
        <p>1.4 billion utility bills are mailed to customers each year. These mailings, they realized, were perfect vehicles for reaching hundreds of millions of households with energy-saving ideas. Come to find out, Robert Cialdini—a renowned behavioral scientist—had academic research that supported their initial ideas about prompting people to change the way they use energy at home. Together, they set about designing a prototype, which they then took on the road to two of America’s major energy markets, California and Texas. The amount of interest they received from utilities, state legislators, and environmental groups soon led to Dan and Alex securing their first round of venture capital funding from MHS Capital.</p>
